<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Saxifraga nidifica </i>is a small perennial herb that colonizes lenses of bare substrates at alpine elevations. This saxifrage and <i>S. bryophora </i>reproduce vegetatively with bulblets that replace flowers in the inflorescence. <i>Antennaria media </i>and <i>Sedum obtusatum </i>reproduce by stolons, and <i>M. rubellus </i>and <i>Polygonum minimum </i>are annuals. These different traits allow the plants to grow at high elevations in unstable areas with short growing seasons. <br/>
<br/>
Stands are local and small in extent in the high Sierra Nevada. Stands of the <i>Penstemon newberryi </i>alliance replace stands of the alliance on drier and warmer sites, and those of the <i>Carex helleri, Oxyria digyna, </i>and <i>Saxifraga tolmiei </i>alliances on wetter and shadier slopes (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands in Harvey Monroe Hall RNA (Taylor 1984, see Cheng 2004) and Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) in the central Sierra Nevada (M261Eo) characterize the alliance. Taylor recognized a <i>Saxifraga nidifica-Mimulus rubellus</i> alliance with four associations: <i>Saxifraga nidifica-Mimulus rubellus, Rhodiola integrifolia-Selaginella watsonii, Saxifraga bryophora</i>, and <i>Polygonum minimum</i>. Keeler-Wolf et al. (2003b) documented an unranked <i>Rhodiola integrifolia-Selaginella watsonii</i> type in Yosemite National Park. We include these types in this provisional alliance. We need more sampling and analysis before understanding affinities of these and other sparsely vegetation herbaceous types at high elevations in the state. </div>
</div>

	

    
